>In article <strnlghtC8HJJv.1zz@netcom.com> strnlght@netcom.com (David Sternlight) writes:
><In article <RM9681.93Jun11172519@eve.albany.edu> rm9681@csc.albany.edu (robert m. marion) writes:
><
><>	When one expresses strong opinions, strong responses may result.
><>	If readers view the enforcement of an encryption method as 
><>being against their own interests, then the boycott of products that
><>use that encryption method is a reasonable response.
><
><This is typical of the irresponsible distortion in this discussion that has
><driven it so out of hand.  Neither Denning nor the government has proposed
><the enforcement of an encryption method.
>
>This may be true but what's wrong with trying to understand where all this
>is leading to?  It is patently clear that Clipper will work as intended
>only assuming all other crypto schemes are made illegal.  If, say,
>triple DES remains legal, Clipper will die the natural death on the market
>because of international compatibility problems (not to mention potential 
>foreign law violations).
>

Not according to my assumptions. I assume other methods to be less secure
than Clipper. If this is true, or even widely believed, then the bad guys
have a choice of an insecure system (which is just fine with the NSA) or
escrowed clipper (which is also fine).  No need to outlaw anything.

